BEGIN:VEVENT
DESCRIPTION:The full eclipse is visible from the western United States a
 nd Canada\, Japan\, eastern China\, and eastern Australasia.\n\nSpeaking
  of China: the Lantern Festival (Yuanxiao Jie) occurs at the end of the 
 lunar year\, concluding Chinese New Year festivities. The night sky is f
 illed with colorful lanterns\, symbolizing good fortune and family reuni
 on. Traditionally\, people celebrate by displaying lanterns\, solving ri
 ddles written on them\, and eating sweet rice balls (tangyuan)\, symboli
 zing unity and wholeness.\n\nAccording to legend\, the Jade Emperor\, ru
 ler of heaven and usually celebrated for being a great friend to humanit
 y\, became enraged when a town killed his favorite sacred goose. In his 
 fury\, he planned to destroy the town with a storm of fire on the 15th l
 unar day. The Jade Emperor's daughter\, sympathizing with the innocent p
 eople\, warned them of her father's plan. The townspeople then lit lante
 rns throughout the town and set off firecrackers to make it appear as if
  the town was already burning. Fooled by this\, the Jade Emperor decided
  not to send down the fire.\n\nPyromaniacs\, get in on the fun! Here's a
  video that shows you how to make your own flying fire lantern: https://
 www.youtube.com/watch?v=mHyAefvWpXA
DTEND:20260303T113749Z
DTSTAMP:20260101T053147Z
DTSTART:20260303T113749Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20251231T234115Z
SUMMARY:🌕 Full Moon\, Total Lunar Eclipse\, and Lantern Festival
TRANSP:OPAQUE
UID:0170-20251231-223153-astrocal@cantonbecker.com
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.timeanddate.com/eclipse/lunar/2026-march-3
END:VEVENT
