BEGIN:VEVENT
CREATED:20250322T152402Z
DESCRIPTION:The waning crescent moon will not be much of a problem this 
 year. Bonus\, you you don't have to wake up early for this one! The radi
 ant point is highest in the sky just as darkness falls.\n\nThe cause of 
 this shower – Comet 21P/Giacobini-Zinner – was at perihelion in March of
  this year. Will we finally see a storm of Draconid meteors this year? Y
 es please!\n\nThe radiant point for the Draconid meteor shower almost co
 incides with the head of the constellation Draco the Dragon in the north
 ern sky. That’s why you can view the Draconids best from the Northern He
 misphere (and early in the Evening.)
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261008
DTSTAMP:20260101T053147Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261007
LAST-MODIFIED:20260101T032755Z
SUMMARY:Draconids Meteor Shower
TRANSP:OPAQUE
UID:0188-20251231-223153-astrocal@cantonbecker.com
URL;VALUE=URI:https://earthsky.org/astronomy-essentials/earthskys-meteor
 -shower-guide/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CREATED:20251231T232201Z
DESCRIPTION:This is an above-average meteor shower\, capable of producin
 g up to 40 meteors per hour at peak.\n\nThe shower runs January 1–5\, pe
 aking overnight on January 3–4. This year it lands squarely on a supermo
 on (doh!)\, washing out all but the brightest shooting stars.\n\nBest vi
 ewing is after midnight from a dark location. Meteors radiate from the c
 onstellation Boötes\, but can appear anywhere in the sky.\n\nThe Quadran
 tids are a memorial to an extinct comet—likely the object known as 2003 
 EH1.
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260105
DTSTAMP:20260101T053147Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260103
LAST-MODIFIED:20251231T232742Z
SUMMARY:Quadrantids Meteor Shower
TRANSP:OPAQUE
UID:0189-20251231-223153-astrocal@cantonbecker.com
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CREATED:20251231T233559Z
DESCRIPTION:This is the best time to try to spot Mercury this year\, whe
 n Mercury is at its greatest western elongation. Look for it before sunr
 ise\, low in the eastern sky.\n\nUnlike our other inner-planet neighbor 
 Venus\, Mercury is hard to see with the naked eye... but it is visible. 
 Are you up for the challenge?\n
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260404
DTSTAMP:20260101T053147Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260403
LAST-MODIFIED:20251231T234416Z
SUMMARY:Mercury Most Visible
TRANSP:OPAQUE
UID:0190-20251231-223153-astrocal@cantonbecker.com
END:VEVENT
